title: For Sale:  Lightly used Ruger sp101
postcontent: I have a lightly used Ruger sp101 for sale. It is chambered in  .357 magnum and has a 2.25" barrel.  The snub nosed revolver is unaltered, and has had 200 rounds fired through it. It is in great working order and good cosmetic condition. It has some minor holster wear on the left side of the barrel and on both sides of the frame forward and above the trigger guard.  It has minor speckles of rust that may have begun to pit slightly. Its very difficult to make out in the pictures, but it is at the outskirts of the grip on the left side. This occurred in the month I had the larger Hogue tamer stocks installed on the pistol. I would imagine it can be buffed out ny a skilled hand, but is reflected in the price. The Ruger sp101 is the shooters snub nosed revolver. It's built like a tank and can steadily digest a consistent amount of even the nastiest .357 rounds. The stainless steel construction adds more weight than its aluminum framed counterparts which decreases recoil tremendously and increases shoot-ability. I love this gun and I had some big plans for it. If you've never seen a Gemini customs sp101 and you like Ruger revolvers you need to check out their custom Rugers. But beware, they are costly! However, There's nothing quite like an all steel gun in a sea of polymer, and to have a craftsman tweak the snub to its max potential is a thing of beauty. I also have 100 rds of .38 spcl40 rounds of 158 gr. Soft point .35730 rounds of Buffalo bore 158 gr. "Tactical short barrel lower recoil low flash .357 mag." I know that's a mouthful but these rounds are, in my opinion, the best .357 defensive rounds to carry in a snub. The recoil is a bit stiffer than a .38 +p but way less stiff than a full power 158 gr .357 magnum and deliver great velocity.I'll add those in for a grand total of $525.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1892 Semi-Deluxe Takedown 25-20
postcontent: Winchester Model 1892 lever action rifle in caliber 25-20 WCF. It is serial # 703784, manufactured approximately 1913. It has the standard 24" round barrel. Special features include the half magazine, takedown option, and very rare 2X uncheckered stocks, along with a shotgun style butt stock (with Whelen-style fluted comb) and hard Winchester rubber butt plate. Barrel and mag exhibit 80% blue with some scratches and wear at the edges, as well as the typical marks from the operation of the takedown lever. Beautiful burl walnut 2X stocks have never been sanded or refinished, do not have any splits or cracks, do not have extra swivel holes, and show only normal usage marks/dings. They are still proud to the metal and fit tightly. Takedown operates normally and is tight with no wobble at junction. Action is crips and strong, half-cock seems to function properly and should make a good shooter upon inspection by a competent gunsmith. Bore has good rifling with very light, scattered pitting typical to the model, also is slightly dark and could use a good cleaning, should clean up to a 7 or 8 of 10. Receiver and lever are in the white, not sure if they were cleaned or just exhibit the normal flaking that was a problem with the bluing process due to the high nickel content of the receivers during this time period. According to Madis's rarity table, 1 of every 3 rifles had a round barrel, one of every 600 guns had special wood, one of every 670 guns had a special butt plate , 4 of every 5 guns was 44 caliber, 2 of every 3 guns was a rifle (no mention of percentage of rifles being takedowns) so this one gets into the highly collectible class with all of its features, especially having deluxe, straight-gripped, uncheckered stocks. The pictures don't do it justice, the flash makes everything too red, the last few pics really show it the best. 3 day inspection allowed and returns accepted as long as firearm has not been fired or taken apart.
